<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900706-0014</DOCNO><DOCID>900706-0014.</DOCID><HL>   What's News --   Business and Finance</HL><DATE>07/06/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1</SO><LP>   A NEW ENERGY TAX is being pushed by the Bushadministration as a way to help cut the budget deficit. Thelevy would bring in an estimated $20 billion a year, morethan any other part of the revenue-raising package beingconsidered. The tax would apply to various sources of energy,including coal and petroleum, and would add five or six centsa gallon to the price of gasoline.   ---</LP><TEXT>   Japanese auto makers grabbed a record 28% share of U.S.car sales in the first half of 1990. Sales of NorthAmerican-made autos, meanwhile, surged 11.9% in late June totheir highest rate in six months.   ---   Hughes Aircraft Chairman Malcolm Currie received some ofthe classified data illicitly obtained by a defense-industryring, court records assert. But a criminal probe of the GMsubsidiary's top officer seems unlikely to lead to anindictment.   ---   Thrift regulators brought administrative charges againstformer Columbia chief Thomas Spiegel. They are seeking $24million for an alleged spending spree with insured deposits.                                                                                                          Charges against Bush's son, an ex-director of a failedSandamp;L, will be heard in public, the government announced.   ---   Avon holders Irwin Jacobs and Amway sold most of theirstake to two Chartwell Associates partners. The deal appearsto give Chartwell, which includes a Mary Kay officer, moreleverage with Avon managers.   ---   Stock prices declined sharply, in part on worry about apossible tax on securities sales. The Dow Jones industrialsfell 32.42 points. Bond prices also sank, and the dollar wasmixed.   ---   The Federal Reserve decided not to ease credit at itsmeeting this week, despite signs of a slowing economy,government officials said.   ---   Stock funds returned an average of 5.89% in the secondquarter, while the Sandamp;P 500 index gained 6.29%. But growth andsmall-company growth funds both returned more than 7%.   ---   Price Waterhouse could face contempt penalties if itviolates securities laws, under a permanent injunction soughtby the SEC. The agency claims the accounting firm is likelyto break the law without such an order.                                                                                                          Accounting firms could do more consulting work for theirauditing clients under an SEC staff ruling.   ---   UAL halted talks with aircraft makers about the purchaseof up to $15 billion in jets, under pressure from a union-ledbuy-out group. The group is offering preferred status tovendors in exchange for financing.   ---   Gannett is expected to post a decline in second-quarterprofit, its first such year-to-year drop in more than twodecades. The reversal signals that an industry slump hasfinally taken hold at the newspaper concern.   ---   An architects trade group settled U.S. charges that itviolated antitrust law by discouraging competitive biddingand discounts by its members.   ---   Bristol-Myers Squibb gave additional duties to WayneDavidson, strengthening his position to be next chiefexecutive and illustrating Bristol Myers's dominance overSquibb since their merger last year.   ---   Anheuser-Busch plans to lead a lobbying effort by brewersto head off a boost in the U.S. excise tax on beer. Thecampaign will include ads condemning the levy as regressive.   ---   Five Players International officials sold $2.5 million ofthe gambling-services firm's stock less than two weeks beforeits price plunged last month.   ---   Markets --   Stocks: Volume 128,320,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials2879.21, off 32.42; transportation 1131.02, off 9.49;utilities 206.17, off 2.77.   Bonds: Shearson Lehman Hutton Treasury index 3456.41, off1.91.   Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 133.88, off 0.22;spot index 134.37, up 0.47.   Dollar: 150.60 yen, off 0.30; 1.6517 marks, up 0.0012.</TEXT></DOC>